The following index definition indexes the `text.en_US` in the
the [sample collection](custom-analyzers-eg-coll) collection using a
custom analyzer named `tokenTrimmer`. The custom analyzer specifies
the following:

- Apply the [htmlStrip](htmlStrip-ref) character filter to remove all HTML
  tags from the text except the `a` tag.

- Apply the [keyword](keyword-tokenizer-ref) to
  create a single token for the entire string.

- Apply the `trim` token filter to remove leading and trailing
  whitespace in the tokens.

**Atlas UI:**

Atlas UI

Visual Editor

- In the Custom Analyzers section, click Add
  Custom Analyzer.

- Select the Create Your Own radio button and click
  Next.

- Type whitespace in the Analyzer Name field.

- Expand Character Filters and click
  &#x20;Add character filter.

- Select mapping from the dropdown and type
  `a` in the ignoredTags field.

- Click Add character filter to add the character filter
  to your custom analyzer.

- Expand Tokenizer if it's collapsed.

- Select whitespace from the dropdown.

- Expand Token Filters and click&#x20;
  Add token filter.

- Select wordDelimiterGraph from the dropdown.

- Click Add token filter to add the token filter to your
  custom analyzer.

- Click Add to add the custom analyzer to your index.

- In the Field Mappings section, click Add
  Field Mapping to apply the custom  analyzer on the
  message field.

- Select message from the Field
  Name dropdown and dateFacet from the Data
  Type dropdown.

- In the properties section for the data type, select whitespace
  from the Index Analyzer and Search Analyzer
  dropdowns.

- Click Add, then Save Changes.

JSON Editor

Replace the default index definition with the following example:

```json
{
  "mappings": {
    "fields": {
      "text": {
        "type": "document",
        "fields": {
          "en_US": {
            "type": "string",
            "analyzer": "tokenTrimmer"
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "tokenTrimmer",
      "charFilters": [{
        "type": "htmlStrip",
        "ignoredTags": ["a"]
      }],
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "keyword"
      },
      "tokenFilters": [
        {
          "type": "trim"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

**Shell:**

MongoDB Shell

```javascript
db.minutes.createSearchIndex("default", {
  "mappings": {
    "fields": {
      "text": {
        "type": "document",
        "fields": {
          "en_US": {
            "type": "string",
            "analyzer": "tokenTrimmer" 
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "analyzers": [
    {
      "name": "tokenTrimmer",
      "charFilters": [{
        "type": "htmlStrip",
        "ignoredTags": ["a"]
      }],
      "tokenizer": {
        "type": "keyword"
      },
      "tokenFilters": [
        {
          "type": "trim"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
})

```

The following query searches for the phrase `*department meetings*`
preceded and followed by any number of other characters in the
`text.en_US` field in the [sample collection](custom-analyzers-eg-coll)
collection.

**Atlas UI:**

Atlas UI

- Click the Query button for your index.

- Click Edit Query to edit the query.

- Click on the query bar and select the database and collection.

- Replace the default query with the following and click
  Search:

  **Input:**

  ```json
  {
    "$search": {
      "wildcard": {
        "query": "*department meetings*",
        "path": "text.en_US",
        "allowAnalyzedField": true
      }
    }
  }
  ```

  **Output:**

  ```js
  SCORE: 1  _id:  "1"
  message: "try to siGn-In"
  page_updated_by: Object
  text: Object
    en_US: "<head> This page deals with department meetings.</head>"
    sv_FI: "Den här sidan behandlar avdelningsmöten"
    fr_CA: "Cette page traite des réunions de département"
  ```

**Shell:**

MongoDB Shell

**Input:**

```json
db.minutes.aggregate([
  {
    "$search": {
      "wildcard": {
        "query": "*department meetings*",
        "path": "text.en_US",
        "allowAnalyzedField": true
      }
    }
  },
  {
    "$project": {
      "_id": 1,
      "text.en_US": 1
    }
  }
])
```

**Output:**

```json
[
  {
    _id: 1,
    text: { en_US: '<head> This page deals with department meetings. </head>' }
  }
]
```

MongoDB Search returns the document with `_id: 1` because the `en_US` field
contains the query term `department meetings`. MongoDB Search creates the
following token for the document in the results, which shows that
MongoDB Search removed the HTML tags, created a single token for the entire
string, and removed leading and trailing whitespaces in the token:

| Document ID | Output Tokens                             |
| ----------- | ----------------------------------------- |
| \_id: 1     | This page deals with department meetings. |

